    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Scheduling Overview",
            Slug = "scheduling-overview",
            Summary = "What production scheduling is, work centers and capacity, shifts, the dispatch list, and how the auto-scheduler assigns operations to time slots.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/scheduling"]""",
            Tags = """["scheduling","planning"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Scheduling Overview\n\nThe Scheduling module turns your production work into a time-based plan. It takes the operations that make up your jobs and assigns each one to a work center (a machine or workstation) at a specific time, while respecting how much capacity that work center actually has. The result is a clear answer to two questions every shop asks every day: *what should I run next*, and *will I hit my due dates*.\n\n### The Five Tabs\n\nThe page is organized into five tabs, each addressing a different part of the planning workflow:\n\n1. **Schedule** — The master list of every scheduled operation. This is where you run the auto-scheduler and lock individual operations so the scheduler leaves them alone. The tab is labeled 'Schedule' and presents the plan as a sortable, filterable data table (one row per operation) — not a graphical Gantt chart with drawn bars. Each row gives you the operation's job, work center, scheduled start/end, hours, status, and lock state.\n2. **Dispatch** — A work-center-specific, priority-ordered list of what to run next. This is the floor-operator view: pick a work center, load its queue.\n3. **Work Centers** — The master data for your production resources. Full create / edit / delete of every machine or workstation.\n4. **Shifts** — The operating-hours definitions (start, end, breaks) that determine how many net working hours exist in a day.\n5. **Run History** — An audit log of every time the scheduler was executed, with how many operations were scheduled and how many conflicts were detected.\n\nThe active tab is stored in the URL, so you can bookmark or share a link straight to the Dispatch or Work Centers view.\n\n### What Is a Work Center?\n\nA **work center** is a physical or logical production resource — a CNC machine, an assembly station, a paint booth, an inspection bench. Scheduling revolves around work centers because they are where capacity is consumed. Each work center has:\n- A short **Code** (e.g., 'CNC-01') and a full **Name**\n- A **Daily Capacity (Hours)** — how many hours of work the center can absorb per day\n- An **Efficiency %** — a realism factor; 100% means the center hits its rated capacity, 85% accounts for downtime, rework, and changeovers\n- A **Number of Machines** — identical units in the center that can run in parallel\n- Optional **Labor Cost / Hour** and **Burden Rate / Hour** for costing\n- An optional link to an **Asset** and a **Location**\n- An **Active / Inactive** flag\n\n### Capacity, Shifts, and Calendars\n\nCapacity is finite. A work center can only do so much in a day, and **shifts** define exactly how much. A shift has a start time, an end time, and break minutes; the system computes the **Net Hours** (end − start − breaks). Multiple shifts let a shop model second and third shifts or round-the-clock operation. Shifts are global — shared across all work centers rather than configured per-center.\n\nWhen scheduled hours approach or exceed a work center's capacity, you have an overload — a conflict the scheduler reports so you can react.\n\n### The Auto-Scheduler and Schedule Runs\n\nThe **scheduler** is an automated engine that assigns operations to work centers and time slots. You trigger it from the Schedule tab with the **Run Scheduler** button — a single click that runs a **forward** pass: starting from today and placing work as early as capacity allows (capacity-driven). There is no direction chooser on the screen; the button always runs forward.\n\nEvery run is recorded: its date, direction, status, the number of operations scheduled, and the number of conflicts detected. The Run History tab is your audit trail of how the plan was built, and its **Direction** column shows the direction each recorded run used (today that is Forward; Backward is a recorded direction the model supports but is not yet selectable from this screen).\n\n### Locking Operations\n\nSometimes you don't want the scheduler to move a particular operation — it's already committed, set up, or promised. From the Schedule tab you can **lock** an operation; the scheduler then treats it as fixed and schedules everything else around it. Toggle the lock icon to lock or unlock.\n\n### The Dispatch List\n\nThe **dispatch list** is the practical, day-to-day output of all this planning. Pick a work center, click Load, and you get a ranked queue of operations in execution order — the 'next up' list a machine operator reads. It shows sequence, scheduled start, setup and run hours, the job's priority, and the job's due date.\n\n### How Scheduling Connects to Other Features\n\n**Jobs and Operations:** Scheduled operations come from the operations defined on your jobs. Each row on the Schedule tab shows a job number and an operation title. Scheduling doesn't invent work — it sequences the work your jobs already describe.\n\n**Assets:** A work center can be linked to an asset (the underlying equipment), tying the scheduling view to the equipment master and, downstream, to maintenance.\n\n**Capacity Planning:** By keeping work-center capacity, efficiency, and shift hours accurate, the schedule reflects reality — overloads surface as conflicts instead of silently slipping due dates.\n\n### When to Use Scheduling\n\n- When you need to know what to run next on a given machine — use Dispatch\n- When you need to rebuild the whole plan after new jobs arrive — Run Scheduler\n- When a particular operation must not move — lock it on the Schedule tab\n- When you add or change a machine or workstation — Work Centers\n- When you change operating hours or add a shift — Shifts\n- When you need to audit how and when the plan was generated — Run History","sections":[]}"""
        });

