            AppRoutes = """["/scheduling"]""",
            Tags = """["scheduling","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Where Shifts and Calendars Are Maintained\n\nThe Scheduling page surfaces a **Shifts** tab, but it is **read-only** — there is no New / Edit / Delete control on it. The tab only lists each shift's name, start time, end time, break minutes, and computed **Net Hours** (end − start − breaks). Shift records themselves are created and edited elsewhere; the backend `ShiftsController` (route `api/v1/shifts`) exposes full GET / POST / PUT / DELETE, gated by `CAP-HR-SHIFTS` and `Authorize(Roles = \"Admin,Manager\")`. Shifts are **global** — shared across every work center, not configured per-center.\n\nThere is no separate working-calendar editor inside Scheduling. Calendar-aware loading (holidays, non-working days) is part of the `CAP-PLAN-CAPACITY` capability's intent, but the only calendar inputs the schedule reads today are the global shift definitions plus each work center's daily capacity / efficiency.\n\n## Asset and Location Are Set Elsewhere\n\nA work center can reference an **Asset** (`assetId` / `assetName`) and a **Company Location** (`companyLocationId` / `locationName`). These are **links to records owned by other modules**, not data you author inside Scheduling:\n\n- The **Asset** is the underlying equipment, maintained in the Assets / Tooling module. The work-center dialog only picks an existing asset; it cannot create one.\n- The **Location** is a `CompanyLocation`, maintained under Admin > Company Settings (Locations). The dialog picks an existing location.\n\nThe Work Centers table shows the resolved `assetName` and `locationName` for reference, but to change the underlying asset or location record you go to its owning module.\n\n## Not-Yet-Exposed Features\n\nThe backend `SchedulingController` ships several endpoints that have **no UI control** on the Scheduling page yet. They exist in the API and the data model but are not wired to a button or interaction:\n\n- **Simulate** — `POST api/v1/scheduling/simulate` runs a what-if scheduling pass without committing. There is no \"Simulate\" button; only the live **Run Scheduler** (`POST .../run`) is exposed.\n- **Drag-to-reschedule** — the Schedule tab is a plain data table, not a graphical Gantt with draggable bars. The per-operation `PATCH api/v1/scheduling/operations/{id}` endpoint can move an operation, but the only schedule edit exposed in the UI is the **lock / unlock** toggle (`POST .../operations/{id}/lock`).\n- **Work-center load** — `GET api/v1/scheduling/work-center-load/{workCenterId}` returns a capacity-utilization view (a `WorkCenterLoad` model the client already imports), but no load / utilization chart is rendered on the page yet.\n\nTreat these as roadmap surface area: the capability and endpoints are present, the interactive UI is not.\n\n## CAP-PLAN-CAPACITY and Role Gating\n\nScheduling is split across three backend controllers, each with its own capability and the same role gate:\n\n- **`CAP-PLAN-CAPACITY`** (default **off**) gates `SchedulingController` — running the scheduler, simulate, gantt, dispatch, work-center load, and operation lock/patch. If this capability is disabled for an install, the Scheduling actions return 403 and the feature is effectively hidden.\n- **`CAP-MD-WORKCENTERS`** gates `WorkCentersController` — work-center create / edit / delete.\n- **`CAP-HR-SHIFTS`** gates `ShiftsController` — shift CRUD (driven from outside the Scheduling page).\n\nAll three controllers carry `[Authorize(Roles = \"Admin,Manager\")]`, so only Admins and Managers can run the scheduler or mutate work centers and shifts. Workers do not have write access here. Because `CAP-PLAN-CAPACITY` is off by default, finite-capacity scheduling is an opt-in capability an admin enables (via `/admin/capabilities` or a preset) before the page does anything useful.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Scheduling training modules");
    }
}
